YES.
In backend APIs, especially in Spring Boot + Hibernate + SQL, we should try to:

* reduce joins
* reduce aggregations
* avoid unnecessary data fetching
* fetch only needed columns

because database operations are usually the biggest bottleneck.

---

# Why Joins and Aggregations Slow APIs

Database needs:

* CPU
* memory
* sorting
* scanning rows
* temporary tables

More joins + aggregations = more processing.

---

# 1. JOIN Problem Example

---

# Scenario

Suppose:

## Orders Table

| id | customer_id | amount |
| -- | ----------- | ------ |
| 1  | 101         | 500    |

---

## Customers Table

| id  | name  | city |
| --- | ----- | ---- |
| 101 | Pavan | Pune |

---

# Bad Query

```sql id="ghzw3s"
SELECT *
FROM orders o
JOIN customers c
ON o.customer_id = c.id;
```

---

# Problems

`SELECT *`
fetches:

* all order columns
* all customer columns

Even if frontend only needs:

* orderId
* customerName

Unnecessary data transferred.

---

# Better Query

```sql id="5lcm4j"
SELECT o.id, c.name
FROM orders o
JOIN customers c
ON o.customer_id = c.id;
```

Fetch only required columns.

Improves:

* memory
* network transfer
* serialization time

---

# Hibernate Best Practice

Instead of:

```java id="g67h9f"
List<Order> findAll();
```

Use DTO projection.

---

# DTO Example

```java id="ksjlwm"
public class OrderResponse {

    private Long orderId;
    private String customerName;

}
```

---

# JPQL Projection

```java id="hj2mns"
@Query("""
SELECT new com.example.dto.OrderResponse(
    o.id,
    c.name
)
FROM Order o
JOIN o.customer c
""")
List<OrderResponse> getOrders();
```

---

# Why Better

Without DTO:

* entire entity loaded
* lazy loading risk
* extra memory

With DTO:

* only required data fetched

Very common optimization in production.

---

# 2. Too Many JOINs Problem

---

# Bad Scenario

```sql id="xjlwm6"
SELECT *
FROM orders o
JOIN customers c ON c.id = o.customer_id
JOIN payments p ON p.order_id = o.id
JOIN products pr ON pr.id = o.product_id
JOIN shipping s ON s.order_id = o.id
JOIN reviews r ON r.product_id = pr.id
```

---

# Problems

Database must:

* join huge tables
* create temporary result sets
* scan many rows

Very slow for large data.

---

# Real Production Fix

Sometimes split into multiple APIs.

Instead of one huge API:

```text id="3aapg4"
GET /order-details
```

Use:

* `/orders`
* `/payments`
* `/shipping`

Frontend calls separately if needed.

---

# Another Fix → Denormalization

Sometimes we store:

* customer_name
* product_name

directly in order table.

To avoid joins.

Used in:

* analytics
* reporting
* high traffic systems

Tradeoff:

* duplicated data
* faster reads

---

# 3. Aggregation Problem

Aggregation:

* COUNT
* SUM
* AVG
* GROUP BY

These are expensive on huge tables.

---

# Bad Example

```sql id="yljlwm"
SELECT customer_id,
       SUM(amount)
FROM orders
GROUP BY customer_id;
```

For millions of rows:

* full table scan
* grouping
* sorting

Heavy query.

---

# Real Scenario

Dashboard API:

```text id="a0hwhv"
total sales
monthly revenue
top customers
```

If calculated live every request:

* slow API
* high DB CPU

---

# Better Solutions

---

# Solution 1 → Cache

Store aggregation result in Redis.

Example:

* refresh every 5 mins

Instead of recalculating every request.

---

# Solution 2 → Precomputed Table

Create summary table.

Example:

## sales_summary

| date       | total_sales |
| ---------- | ----------- |
| 2026-05-01 | 50000       |

Update periodically using:

* cron jobs
* Kafka consumers
* batch jobs

Now query becomes:

```sql id="x8exkh"
SELECT total_sales
FROM sales_summary
WHERE date='2026-05-01';
```

Very fast.

---

# Solution 3 → Async Processing

Heavy analytics:

* Kafka
* batch processing

Instead of calculating during API request.

---

# 4. N+1 Query Problem

Very common Hibernate performance issue.

---

# Bad Code

```java id="4nfdm5"
List<Order> orders = orderRepository.findAll();

for(Order order : orders){
    System.out.println(order.getCustomer().getName());
}
```

If lazy loading:

* 1 query for orders
* N queries for customers

Total:

```text id="nj2hmh"
1 + N queries
```

Very slow.

---

# Fix

Use fetch join.

```java id="qu1zqn"
@Query("""
SELECT o
FROM Order o
JOIN FETCH o.customer
""")
List<Order> getOrders();
```

---

# 5. Pagination Important

Never fetch huge data.

Bad:

```java id="lm0zln"
findAll()
```

Good:

```java id="3dz6f0"
findAll(pageable)
```

---

# 6. Indexing

Without index:

```sql id="2jlwmu"
WHERE email='abc@gmail.com'
```

DB scans all rows.

---

# Add Index

```sql id="xq4bq3"
CREATE INDEX idx_email
ON users(email);
```

Huge performance improvement.

---

# 7. Avoid SELECT *

Bad:

```sql id="yjlwmk"
SELECT *
```

Good:

```sql id="d2snjs"
SELECT id, name
```

---

# 8. Use Read-Optimized APIs

Example:

Frontend needs:

* username
* profile image

Do not return:

* password
* address
* audit fields
* huge nested objects

Use lightweight DTOs.

